  "body": "Title: Envoy build fails with GCC 7.2.\r\n\r\nDescription:\r\n```\r\nERROR: /root/.cache/bazel/_bazel_root/e3bb2978717df7858b43846d8c1242eb/external/envoy/source/common/upstream/BUILD:334:1: C++ compilation of rule '@envoy//source/common/upstream:upstream_lib' failed (Exit 1)\r\nexternal/envoy/source/common/upstream/upstream_impl.cc: In static member function 'static Envoy::Network::ClientConnectionPtr Envoy::Upstream::HostImpl::createConnection(Envoy::Event::Dispatcher&, const Envoy::Upstream::ClusterInfo&, Envoy::Network::Address::InstanceConstSharedPtr, const OptionsSharedPtr&)':\r\nexternal/envoy/source/common/upstream/upstream_impl.cc:80:67: error: '*((void*)& iftmp.712 +1)' may be used uninitialized in this function [-Werror=maybe-uninitialized]\r\n                                           : absl::optional<bool>{}) {}\r\n                                                                   ^\r\ncc1plus: all warnings being treated as errors\r\nTarget //:envoy_deps failed to build\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe failure happens due to the compiler issuing the `maybe-uninitialized` warning (enabled via `-Wall`), which is considered as an error due to `-Werror` compiler option. GCC, however, reserves the freedom of issuing false positive `maybe-uninitialized` warnings (hence the 'maybe-'), and apparently clang does not turn on `maybe-uninitialized` warning via `-Wall` for this reason.\r\n\r\nThis seems to be a well-known issue affecting `std`, `boost` and `absl` variants of `optional`, see, e.g., https://stackoverflow.com/questions/21755206/how-to-get-around-gcc-void-b-4-may-be-used-uninitialized-in-this-funct.\r\n\r\nA potential solution would be to not issue `maybe-uninitialized` warnings also with gcc by setting `-Wno-maybe-uninitialized` after `-Wall` or at least not considering them as errors by adding the option `-Wno-error=maybe-uninitialized` after `-Werror`.",
